WEBVTT

00:04.047 --> 00:04.265
.

00:04.308 --> 00:06.789
- I'll be targeting
your cancer directly

00:06.832 --> 00:08.486
with stereotactic body
radiotherapy--

00:08.530 --> 00:10.314
- With simultaneous intravenous
Cis-Platinum.

00:10.358 --> 00:12.055
Two-cycle regiment.

00:12.099 --> 00:14.014
- And I may throw in an EGFR
inhibitor like cetuximab,

00:14.057 --> 00:15.537
depending on how
your tumor responds.

00:15.580 --> 00:16.755
- Works for me.

00:16.799 --> 00:19.323
- In English, please.

00:19.367 --> 00:22.544
It sounds very important
but, um,

00:22.587 --> 00:26.069
all I care about is...

00:26.113 --> 00:28.506
Could he...

00:28.550 --> 00:30.639
[solemn music]

00:30.682 --> 00:31.814
What are his odds?

00:31.857 --> 00:33.207
- Georgia.
- No, Max.

00:33.250 --> 00:34.686
I need an answer from
your doctor.

00:34.730 --> 00:37.080
♪

00:37.124 --> 00:41.693
- Georgia, with cancer,

00:41.737 --> 00:44.696
the odds are difficult
to quantify.

00:44.740 --> 00:47.612
But I believe that this
is our very best option.

00:47.656 --> 00:49.440
♪

00:49.484 --> 00:52.443
- So why haven't
we started already?

00:52.487 --> 00:53.792
♪

00:53.836 --> 00:55.577
- Yes, Max,

00:55.620 --> 00:57.405
why haven't we started already?

00:58.797 --> 01:01.670
- B-Because there's a lot
of pre-treatment procedures

01:01.713 --> 01:02.714
I still need to get done.

01:02.758 --> 01:05.152
Like, um, radiation tattoo,

01:05.195 --> 01:07.110
oral surgery...
- Oral surgery?

01:07.154 --> 01:09.634
- Max's back molars will fall
into the field of radiation

01:09.678 --> 01:11.201
and they'll need
to be extracted.

01:11.245 --> 01:13.464
- Um, so why haven't
we done that yet?

01:16.728 --> 01:18.600
- Because I have been kicking
this thing down the road,

01:18.643 --> 01:20.558
a little bit.

01:20.602 --> 01:23.474
To try to buy myself
a little more time,

01:23.518 --> 01:28.175
you know,
as--as medical director.

01:28.218 --> 01:31.134
Which, now that
I say out loud,

01:31.178 --> 01:33.789
in front of my wife,
does not sound like the excuse

01:33.832 --> 01:35.747
it sounded like in my head.

01:35.791 --> 01:38.402
- Hmm, ya think?
- Yep.

01:38.446 --> 01:40.709
- Could he have his molars
out today?

01:40.752 --> 01:42.276
- That's up to him.

01:42.319 --> 01:44.147
- We have the big
Domino Transplant today.

01:44.191 --> 01:47.194
The run-through's in 30.
I can't, uh--if I'm...

01:47.237 --> 01:51.546
But I think I could
because once they start,

01:51.589 --> 01:53.156
they don't really--
they don't really need me.

01:53.200 --> 01:56.551
And I could probably be free
as early as tomorrow.

01:56.594 --> 01:57.856
♪

01:57.900 --> 02:00.163
Today...

02:00.207 --> 02:01.469
Early afternoon.

02:01.512 --> 02:03.862
- You're on board.
- I'm on board.

02:03.906 --> 02:06.604
- Just like that?
- Just like that.

02:06.648 --> 02:10.391
♪

02:10.434 --> 02:11.696
- Domino day.
- Yeah.

02:11.740 --> 02:14.438
- You excited?
- Um, eh.

02:14.482 --> 02:16.484
Transplant surgeons
get to have all the fun.

02:16.527 --> 02:17.746
I don't even get
to sing back-up.

02:17.789 --> 02:19.443
- [chuckles]

02:19.487 --> 02:21.184
- You know, I had a really
good time last night.

02:21.228 --> 02:22.881
And the night before.

02:22.925 --> 02:24.796
I hope you did too.

02:24.840 --> 02:26.276
- Mm.

02:26.320 --> 02:27.451
- What?

02:27.495 --> 02:29.540
- [laughs]

02:29.584 --> 02:31.412
I did.

02:31.455 --> 02:33.153
- I really like where
this is going.

02:33.196 --> 02:35.242
You know?
You and me.

02:35.285 --> 02:36.895
- You sound so surprised.

02:36.939 --> 02:40.595
- No, no, I, um,
I just didn't think

02:40.638 --> 02:42.597
I don't know.

02:42.640 --> 02:44.642
I don't know what I thought.

02:44.686 --> 02:48.429
- Well, when Lauren
introduced us I had a feeling.

02:51.867 --> 02:54.261
- So, uh, what do you say?

02:54.304 --> 02:56.176
We probably shouldn't walk in
together, right?

02:56.219 --> 02:58.743
- Oh, yeah.
It's way too soon.

02:58.787 --> 03:01.398
I don't know about you,
but on our side of the building

03:01.442 --> 03:03.705
we're real gossipy.

03:11.539 --> 03:13.802
I'll see you later.

03:19.416 --> 03:22.376
[exciting music]

03:22.419 --> 03:26.249
♪

03:26.293 --> 03:28.425
- Haven't I told you about
drinking those things?

03:28.469 --> 03:29.600
You end up bouncing off
the walls

03:29.644 --> 03:30.732
and annoying the other nurses.

03:30.775 --> 03:32.299
- Yeah, that's part
of my charm.

03:32.342 --> 03:33.648
Besides, I need it.

03:33.691 --> 03:34.823
- Pull another double?

03:34.866 --> 03:35.867
- Bronx General.

03:35.911 --> 03:37.260
- "Knife and Gun Club?"

03:37.304 --> 03:38.348
- A guy's gotta eat.

03:38.392 --> 03:39.871
Man, their ED never stops.

03:39.915 --> 03:41.786
- They need docs?

03:41.830 --> 03:43.266
- Since when are you hard up
for cash?

03:43.310 --> 03:44.876
- I'm not.
It sounds like fun.

03:44.920 --> 03:47.009
- Don't you just ever wanna
go home and do nothing?

03:47.052 --> 03:49.403
- Now where's the fun in that?

03:51.405 --> 03:53.711
Hi, I'm Dr. Bloom.

03:53.755 --> 03:56.888
- Diego.
My daughter, Gianna.

03:56.932 --> 03:58.499
- Hi, Gianna.

03:58.542 --> 04:00.631
So you're having some trouble
breathing?

04:00.675 --> 04:02.416
- It's getting worse.

04:02.459 --> 04:04.896
I waited too long.

04:04.940 --> 04:07.334
We can't--
- Papa is...

04:07.377 --> 04:08.944
Worried...

04:08.987 --> 04:11.425
you can't help us.

04:11.468 --> 04:13.340
- You don't have insurance?

04:13.383 --> 04:15.733
- Undocumented.

04:15.777 --> 04:17.692
- Well, we treat everyone here.

04:17.735 --> 04:20.564
You're safe from ICE.

04:20.608 --> 04:22.305
If that's what
you're worried about.

04:22.349 --> 04:24.916
They won't even know
you were here.

04:24.960 --> 04:26.004
Come on.
Pop, up Gianna.

04:26.048 --> 04:27.571
Let's have a listen.

04:31.445 --> 04:33.055
"Sandstorm," huh?

04:33.098 --> 04:35.753
- You...know it?

04:35.797 --> 04:37.451
- Obsessed.

04:37.494 --> 04:39.583
Been collecting single issues
since the '90s.

04:39.627 --> 04:41.542
- [heavy breathing]

04:41.585 --> 04:42.847
- Deep breath.

04:44.327 --> 04:45.415
Again.

04:45.459 --> 04:48.679
- [labored breathing]

04:48.723 --> 04:51.465
- Good.
Good.

04:51.508 --> 04:54.468
[solemn music]

04:54.511 --> 04:56.818
You, uh, have you seen
the platinum issue?

04:57.732 --> 05:00.343
Gemini, she steals
the Halter Cross

05:00.387 --> 05:01.344
from the fourth dimension.

05:01.388 --> 05:02.911
It's wicked.

05:02.954 --> 05:06.958
- Gemini's... my favorite.

05:07.002 --> 05:09.613
[labored breathing]

05:09.657 --> 05:11.398
- I'll be right back.

05:11.441 --> 05:13.400
♪

05:13.443 --> 05:15.924
Casey, I need a chest x-ray,

05:15.967 --> 05:17.447
and I need you
to page Reynolds.

05:17.491 --> 05:19.449
I need him now.

05:27.457 --> 05:29.981
- You got anything that will
anchor the roll?

05:30.025 --> 05:32.419
- Ooh, science project?

05:32.462 --> 05:35.073
- Yeah, living that
extra credit dream.

05:35.117 --> 05:36.901
- Yeah, I can see that.

05:36.945 --> 05:38.425
- Domino run-through.

05:38.468 --> 05:39.904
No time for chitchat.
- Yes, I know.

05:39.948 --> 05:41.819
Do you always have to be
such a buzzkill?

05:43.691 --> 05:45.388
- How is she being a buzzkill?

05:45.432 --> 05:47.912
- Oh, um--well, do you
remember how

05:47.956 --> 05:50.045
I said I was gonna try to
pull some strings for Blanca?

05:52.482 --> 05:54.092
- You couldn't do it.
Figured.

05:54.136 --> 05:56.660
- Mmm, oh, you figured,
did you?

05:56.704 --> 05:58.619
Yeah, well, figure this,

05:58.662 --> 06:00.490
my friend at Family Services
got Blanca named

06:00.534 --> 06:02.884
an Emergency Foster Provider.

06:02.927 --> 06:04.755
Boom.

06:06.714 --> 06:08.890
She had a site visit
this morning.

06:08.933 --> 06:10.152
Boom.

06:10.195 --> 06:11.849
Guess what else.

06:11.893 --> 06:13.590
- Something that ends
in "boom?"

06:13.634 --> 06:16.854
- Uh, yeah.
She passed with flying colors.

06:18.073 --> 06:19.727
You got a home.

06:19.770 --> 06:22.730
[soft piano music]

06:22.773 --> 06:26.516
♪

06:26.560 --> 06:27.865
- Really?

06:27.909 --> 06:29.476
- Yes.

06:31.652 --> 06:33.044
- They can't take it back?

06:33.088 --> 06:35.525
- No, there are no backsies
on this boom.

06:35.569 --> 06:37.484
Okay, by this time tomorrow,

06:37.527 --> 06:39.834
you're gonna be moving into
your brand new digs.

06:39.877 --> 06:41.052
♪

06:41.096 --> 06:43.446
Trust me, it's good.
All right?

06:43.490 --> 06:45.666
- Yeah.

06:45.709 --> 06:48.886
- Okay, I better go
before I have to relocate.

06:48.930 --> 06:50.192
I'll see you later.

06:50.235 --> 06:57.417
♪

07:03.510 --> 07:10.517
♪

07:26.489 --> 07:28.056
- Dr. Albert?
- Here.

07:28.099 --> 07:29.884
- Dr. Franz?
- We're here.

07:29.927 --> 07:31.538
- We've got Pittsburgh
and Newark.

07:31.581 --> 07:33.583
- Morning.
Uh, Max Goodwin here.

07:33.627 --> 07:35.846
I'm the new Medical Director
at New Amsterdam,

07:35.890 --> 07:38.109
and just to confirm,
you are both in charge

07:38.153 --> 07:39.720
of your respective
harvest teams?

07:39.763 --> 07:40.938
- Yes.
- Correct.

07:40.982 --> 07:43.245
- Great.
Dr. Sharpe here has been

07:43.288 --> 07:45.595
working on this project
for the last seven months,

07:45.639 --> 07:49.033
so it is our job to
not screw it up for her.

07:49.077 --> 07:51.253
To that end,
I would like to take everyone

07:51.296 --> 07:53.951
through the Domino Transplant
Chain one last time

07:53.995 --> 07:56.867
set to the illustrious tunes
of Mr. Van Morrison.

07:56.911 --> 07:58.652
- Max.

07:58.695 --> 07:59.957
- I'm just getting everyone
pumped for the dry run.

08:00.001 --> 08:01.829
Am I right, Newark?

08:03.526 --> 08:05.920
Not a Van Morrison fan.
What about Pittsburgh?

08:05.963 --> 08:07.008
- [coughing]

08:07.051 --> 08:08.009
- Yeah, all right, moving on.

08:08.052 --> 08:09.532
We have six patients

08:09.576 --> 08:11.534
receiving partial
liver transplants today,

08:11.578 --> 08:13.797
and, uh, six living donors
from three states.

08:13.841 --> 08:16.974
Our first donor surgery
will be Tanya Mayer.

08:17.018 --> 08:18.759
She just arrived at JFK.

08:18.802 --> 08:20.630
Dr. Kapoor is running point
on her.

08:20.674 --> 08:23.024
Except Tanya isn't a match
for her brother, Matthew.

08:23.067 --> 08:26.244
So a lobe of her liver
will be going to Aminah Ali.

08:26.288 --> 08:29.247
- My patient.
Aminah is the anchor patient.

08:29.291 --> 08:31.206
Her HLA factors were difficult
to match.

08:31.249 --> 08:32.990
That's why it took so long
to find her a donor.

08:33.034 --> 08:34.818
- Each of our recipients
couldn't find a donor match

08:34.862 --> 08:36.690
within their own families,
so their families agreed

08:36.733 --> 08:39.562
to donate to someone else
who would be a match for them.

08:39.606 --> 08:43.566
Aminah's husband, Tariq,
will donate to Francis Potter.

08:43.610 --> 08:45.568
His mother, Lily Potter,
will then donate

08:45.612 --> 08:47.135
to Beck Newman.

08:47.178 --> 08:50.878
Omar Kahn in Newark
will donate to Lisa Verdad

08:50.921 --> 08:52.532
here at New Amsterdam.

08:52.575 --> 08:54.969
Mina Verdad will donate
to Gil Hess.

08:55.012 --> 08:57.667
And last but not least,
to close the loop,

08:57.711 --> 08:59.843
Peter Stern in Pittsburgh
will donate

08:59.887 --> 09:02.193
to our very own, Matthew Levy.

09:02.237 --> 09:04.544
- It's like Hands Across
America but with livers.

09:05.893 --> 09:08.330
[laughter]

09:08.373 --> 09:10.027
Oh, yeah.
I'll be here all week, Newark.

09:10.071 --> 09:11.159
Thank you.

09:11.202 --> 09:12.813
- [quietly] Wow.

09:12.856 --> 09:15.032
Um, all these surgeries
are time sensitive.

09:15.076 --> 09:17.687
All right, let's, uh,
give this our best shot.

09:17.731 --> 09:20.951
And Dr. Sharpe...
bravo.

09:20.995 --> 09:22.736
♪

09:24.041 --> 09:26.043
[light knocking]
- Knock, knock.

09:26.087 --> 09:28.742
How's the superstar
doing today?

09:29.612 --> 09:31.701
- So happy the waiting's
finally over.

09:31.745 --> 09:34.051
- Dr. Sharpe, back when Aminah
was going through chemo,

09:34.095 --> 09:36.184
I used to hate seeing you.

09:36.227 --> 09:38.055
But now...

09:38.099 --> 09:39.230
[muttering]

09:39.274 --> 09:41.145
- Oh.
- Tariq, she's a doctor.

09:41.189 --> 09:42.582
Have some respect.

09:42.625 --> 09:43.800
- Sorry.
- [laughs]

09:43.844 --> 09:45.846
- She's like family, umi.

09:45.889 --> 09:48.022
- Is the young lady
who's donating here yet?

09:48.065 --> 09:49.589
We would like to meet her.

09:49.632 --> 09:51.242
- Tanya should be arriving
any moment.

09:51.286 --> 09:54.245
[percussive jazz music]

09:54.289 --> 10:01.252
♪

10:01.296 --> 10:03.124
- Hey, T.

10:04.778 --> 10:06.867
You're looking good.

10:06.910 --> 10:09.260
How are the kids?

10:09.304 --> 10:12.655
- You know, they each have
their own bedroom now.

10:12.699 --> 10:15.919
So they kinda love that.

10:15.963 --> 10:17.834
- Until they told me
you'd landed...

10:19.183 --> 10:21.185
I wasn't sure
you'd get on that plane.

10:22.796 --> 10:23.840
- Me either.

10:23.884 --> 10:26.930
[melancholy music]

10:27.714 --> 10:28.976
But I got over it.

10:29.019 --> 10:31.935
It's for a good cause, right?

10:31.979 --> 10:35.722
♪

10:35.765 --> 10:37.854
- Family.

10:37.898 --> 10:40.117
♪

10:40.161 --> 10:42.380
- So this part of my liver,

10:42.424 --> 10:44.078
why can't it go straight
to Matty?

10:44.121 --> 10:46.689
- You're not a donor match
for your brother.

10:46.733 --> 10:49.126
The same is true for everyone
in the chain.

10:49.170 --> 10:51.085
Not a match
for their own family

10:51.128 --> 10:52.869
but a match for someone else's.

10:52.913 --> 10:55.176
- Sounds complicated.

10:55.219 --> 10:56.743
- It is.

10:56.786 --> 10:59.746
But also very simple
in the end.

10:59.789 --> 11:00.834
Everyone lives.

11:00.877 --> 11:02.923
♪

11:02.966 --> 11:04.664
[percussive jazz music]

11:04.707 --> 11:05.926
- Where's Reynolds this time?

11:05.969 --> 11:07.144
- We're not doing this again,
are we?

11:07.188 --> 11:08.755
He's busy.

11:08.798 --> 11:10.321
- He's been busy for the past
three days,

11:10.365 --> 11:12.715
whenever I need a consult.

11:12.759 --> 11:14.717
Gianna, this is Dr. Flores.

11:14.761 --> 11:17.851
She specializes in cheekiness
and lungs.

11:18.765 --> 11:20.027
- Cool.

11:20.070 --> 11:21.985
- Do you know what's wrong
with my daughter?

11:22.029 --> 11:23.291
- I do.

11:23.334 --> 11:25.119
Scattered interstitial
infiltrates

11:25.162 --> 11:26.381
on the chest x-ray.

11:26.424 --> 11:28.209
[speaking in Spanish]

11:44.747 --> 11:46.444
Dr. Bloom.

11:51.058 --> 11:53.843
♪

11:53.887 --> 11:55.845
- We miss you, Mommy.

11:55.889 --> 11:58.848
- Hope you have
a good surgery.

12:00.545 --> 12:02.025
- Hello, Ms. Mayer.
I'm Dr. Frome.

12:02.069 --> 12:03.766
We spoke on the phone.

12:03.810 --> 12:06.290
- You have to do some kind
of psych evaluation?

12:06.334 --> 12:07.509
- I do, yes.

12:07.552 --> 12:09.076
Just to, you know, make sure

12:09.119 --> 12:10.294
that you understand
what you're getting into

12:10.338 --> 12:12.166
before you give
your liver away.

12:12.209 --> 12:14.124
- Part of my liver.

12:14.168 --> 12:16.213
- Right, yes.

12:16.257 --> 12:18.085
One step ahead of me.
Good.

12:18.128 --> 12:20.914
Okay, just a few questions
that aren't

12:20.957 --> 12:23.046
on the forms you sent me.

12:23.090 --> 12:25.440
First, I need to confirm
that you are doing this

12:25.483 --> 12:26.963
of your own free will.

12:27.007 --> 12:28.748
Under no pressure
from anyone else.

12:28.791 --> 12:31.185
- I'm doing this because
my brother asked me to.

12:33.883 --> 12:35.450
- Siblings, am I right?
[chuckles]

12:38.366 --> 12:40.542
- Do you have a brother,
Dr. Frome?

12:43.414 --> 12:46.113
- I did, yes.
He passed away.

12:46.156 --> 12:49.899
- Would you have given him

12:49.943 --> 12:53.163
part of yourself to save him
if you could've?

12:54.948 --> 12:57.907
- [clears throat]
Yeah.

12:57.951 --> 12:59.866
But you don't get do-overs,
right?

13:04.609 --> 13:07.221
Okay, why don't we talk about
post-op care?

13:07.264 --> 13:08.352
[solemn music]

13:08.396 --> 13:10.224
Tanya?

13:10.267 --> 13:12.226
Are you all right?

13:12.269 --> 13:15.055
- [crying]

13:15.098 --> 13:16.534
♪

13:16.578 --> 13:18.232
- What do you mean she's out?

13:18.275 --> 13:20.147
- I mean she's out, Max.
I can't clear her for surgery.

13:20.190 --> 13:21.931
- I don't believe this.

13:21.975 --> 13:24.368
- This house of cards is built
entirely on her consent.

13:24.412 --> 13:27.023
- Listen, Tanya Mayer
is nowhere near emotionally

13:27.067 --> 13:28.895
or psychologically capable
of being a donor.

13:28.938 --> 13:30.853
- What--what exactly
did she say?

13:30.897 --> 13:32.812
- Well, she's got
two small kids.

13:32.855 --> 13:34.465
She's worried she won't
be able to take care of them

13:34.509 --> 13:35.858
while she's in recovery.

13:35.902 --> 13:37.555
- What's the real reason?

13:37.599 --> 13:39.470
- [sighs]
On a deeper level,

13:39.514 --> 13:42.386
on a more emotional,
personal level...

13:42.430 --> 13:43.866
She's not convinced that Matty

13:43.910 --> 13:45.433
would make the same sacrifice
for her.

13:45.476 --> 13:47.087
- She can't be serious.

13:47.130 --> 13:49.089
- They are deep wounds
in this relationship,

13:49.132 --> 13:51.004
Kapoor, old ones.
- They're family.

13:51.047 --> 13:52.396
- Can't you talk to her?

13:52.440 --> 13:53.528
- Anything I say to her
at this point

13:53.571 --> 13:54.921
could be construed as coercion.

13:54.964 --> 13:56.139
- No one is suggesting
coercion.

13:56.183 --> 13:57.924
- Stop.
Look at this board.

13:57.967 --> 13:59.142
[dramatic music]

13:59.186 --> 14:00.274
Look at these people.

14:00.317 --> 14:01.275
♪

14:01.318 --> 14:04.365
How do we fix this chain?

14:04.408 --> 14:06.019
♪

14:08.630 --> 14:08.848
.

14:08.891 --> 14:12.286
- Are you saying the chain's
in jeopardy

14:12.329 --> 14:13.548
and we might need to pull the
plug on Omar Kahn's surgery?

14:13.591 --> 14:14.854
- Well, let's just call it
a pause.

14:14.897 --> 14:16.507
- We can't hold the OR
forever.

14:16.551 --> 14:17.900
- I know, just give us
some time to regroup.

14:17.944 --> 14:19.380
If we can put this thing
back together,

14:19.423 --> 14:21.338
then we are gonna need
your donor.

14:21.382 --> 14:22.600
- Keep us in the loop.

14:22.644 --> 14:23.819
- Thanks.
Any luck?

14:23.863 --> 14:25.299
- We have been on the phone

14:25.342 --> 14:26.300
with the Organ Transplant
Foundation

14:26.343 --> 14:27.605
for the last couple hours.

14:27.649 --> 14:29.303
No match for Aminah.

14:29.346 --> 14:31.653
- The same with
the Living Donor Network.

14:31.696 --> 14:33.220
- Okay.

14:33.263 --> 14:35.309
So what now?

14:35.352 --> 14:37.311
- We keep looking.
The chain depends on it.

14:39.922 --> 14:41.315
- What if it didn't?

14:41.358 --> 14:42.577
[dramatic music]

14:42.620 --> 14:43.578
- We might need
a few more words

14:43.621 --> 14:45.449
there from you, Boss.

14:45.493 --> 14:46.711
- We can still move forward
with most

14:46.755 --> 14:48.800
of the surgeries today.

14:48.844 --> 14:50.585
- Don't even say it.

14:50.628 --> 14:51.891
- Tanya is gone, all right?

14:51.934 --> 14:53.414
Aminah doesn't have a donor,

14:53.457 --> 14:56.156
but the rest of these
recipients do.

14:56.199 --> 14:58.549
- Because of Aminah.

14:58.593 --> 15:00.203
She's the anchor patient.

15:00.247 --> 15:02.553
We started this chain
to find her an organ.

15:02.597 --> 15:04.555
Without her and Tariq,
there would be no chain.

15:04.599 --> 15:07.558
- I know, and we will find
Aminah a donor.

15:07.602 --> 15:09.473
Just not today.

15:09.517 --> 15:12.433
- Will Tariq agree to donate
without Aminah having a donor?

15:12.476 --> 15:13.956
♪

15:14.000 --> 15:15.871
- It's the right thing to do.

15:15.915 --> 15:18.961
- The right thing to do?

15:19.005 --> 15:20.615
That he should give up
a piece of himself

15:20.658 --> 15:22.747
while we take away
his wife's hope?

15:22.791 --> 15:25.881
- This is the best option
we have.

15:25.925 --> 15:28.710
♪

15:28.753 --> 15:30.799
- I'm sorry to cause
so much trouble.

15:30.842 --> 15:32.670
- It wasn't you.
It was Tanya.

15:34.498 --> 15:36.674
- No, I-I knew it was risky.

15:36.718 --> 15:38.241
♪

15:38.285 --> 15:40.722
We haven't been close
in a long time.

15:40.765 --> 15:42.593
She has her own family now--

15:42.637 --> 15:44.204
- She promised you, Matty.

15:44.247 --> 15:45.901
She broke her promise.

15:45.945 --> 15:49.470
And now because of her,
a woman across the hall is...

15:51.385 --> 15:54.431
[intense music]

15:55.476 --> 15:57.565
- Would you give me a second?

15:57.608 --> 15:58.958
Hey.
Hey.

15:59.001 --> 16:00.916
- What kind of a person
makes a promise,

16:00.960 --> 16:02.352
gets on to a plane
and then throws

16:02.396 --> 16:03.571
that promise in your face?

16:03.614 --> 16:05.747
- Um, a mother who's scared
to die?

16:05.790 --> 16:07.531
A sister who feels used?

16:07.575 --> 16:09.011
- Where I come from, that's not
how we treat our family.

16:09.055 --> 16:10.578
We don't turn our back on them.

16:10.621 --> 16:11.796
- Oh, okay, Vijay.

16:11.840 --> 16:13.494
This is not about
you and your son.

16:13.537 --> 16:15.017
You can't make this about
him turning his back on you.

16:15.061 --> 16:17.889
- Iggy, you are most welcome
to play psychiatrist

16:17.933 --> 16:21.545
with everyone else in
this hospital, not me.

16:21.589 --> 16:27.029
♪

16:27.073 --> 16:30.293
- So no transplant today.

16:30.337 --> 16:32.034
- I am so sorry, Aminah.

16:32.078 --> 16:33.862
- Did the donor say why?

16:33.905 --> 16:35.559
- We can't ask those kinds
of questions,

16:35.603 --> 16:38.040
but we are searching
for a new donor right now.

16:38.084 --> 16:40.782
- It took seven months
to get here.

16:40.825 --> 16:42.784
Aminah doesn't have another
seven months.

16:42.827 --> 16:44.655
- Neither do the others
in the chain.

16:44.699 --> 16:47.267
- What happens to them?

16:47.310 --> 16:50.357
- Many of the other recipients
are very sick.

16:50.400 --> 16:53.055
They're much sicker than you.

16:53.099 --> 16:54.622
- Allah yarhamahum.

16:54.665 --> 16:57.755
- That's why we...

16:57.799 --> 17:01.455
That's why we need to proceed
with the other surgeries today.

17:01.498 --> 17:03.892
[dramatic music]

17:03.935 --> 17:05.850
- You're what?

17:05.894 --> 17:08.723
- We need to--
I need to ask you--

17:08.766 --> 17:10.290
- You can't be serious.

17:10.333 --> 17:12.683
- You would be saving
so many lives.

17:12.727 --> 17:14.685
- By sacrificing my wife's.

17:14.729 --> 17:15.991
- Tariq.
- No.

17:16.035 --> 17:17.993
No, no, no.
Hey, I love you.

17:18.037 --> 17:20.430
I am not gonna let them
do this to you.

17:20.474 --> 17:21.649
♪

17:21.692 --> 17:22.780
- The Qur'an teaches us that--

17:22.824 --> 17:24.869
- Not now, umi.

17:24.913 --> 17:27.698
- I know that it seems unfair--

17:27.742 --> 17:29.048
- I won't do it.

17:29.091 --> 17:30.614
♪

17:30.658 --> 17:32.355
Not unless Aminah has a donor.

17:32.399 --> 17:36.316
♪

17:36.359 --> 17:37.447
- This should relieve
the pressure

17:37.491 --> 17:39.014
building up in Gianna's lungs.

17:39.058 --> 17:41.538
- I'm through the right atrium.

17:41.582 --> 17:43.453
So is there a reason
you keep sending me

17:43.497 --> 17:46.456
to do ED consults
when Dr. Bloom's on duty?

17:48.110 --> 17:49.372
- Do I need a reason?

17:49.416 --> 17:50.852
- I get the sense Dr. Bloom

17:50.895 --> 17:52.506
thinks you're avoiding her.

17:52.549 --> 17:55.509
That or she has no confidence
in my abilities.

17:55.552 --> 17:57.859
- She thinks you're
an excellent surgeon.

17:57.902 --> 17:59.513
It's just that, uh,

17:59.556 --> 18:02.907
she and I have a bit
of a situation.

18:02.951 --> 18:05.127
- Oh...
- No, no, no.

18:05.171 --> 18:06.433
[chuckles]
Not like that.

18:06.476 --> 18:08.043
- Well, whatever it is,

18:08.087 --> 18:09.871
may I suggest you start
answering your own pages?

18:11.002 --> 18:12.743
[beeping]

18:14.397 --> 18:16.704
Right Ventricular
pressure's 35.

18:16.747 --> 18:20.055
♪

18:20.099 --> 18:22.666
- Draining the fluid
didn't work.

18:22.710 --> 18:24.538
- I got your page.
What's up?

18:24.581 --> 18:26.583
- Jemma had an impulsive
aggression episode.

18:26.627 --> 18:27.802
- How bad?

18:27.845 --> 18:29.586
♪

18:29.630 --> 18:31.110
- The other students
said it came out of nowhere.

18:31.153 --> 18:33.155
She was screaming,
throwing things.

18:33.199 --> 18:36.071
We put her in a quiet room
to calm down, but...

18:36.115 --> 18:38.465
- It's not my fault!

18:38.508 --> 18:39.901
- Not so quiet.

18:39.944 --> 18:41.598
- Do you think we need
to pump the brakes

18:41.642 --> 18:43.122
on Jemma's home placement?

18:43.165 --> 18:44.471
- It's not my fault.

18:44.514 --> 18:47.604
It's not my fault!

18:48.214 --> 18:50.041
- So your daughter has
a condition called

18:50.085 --> 18:51.956
idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis,

18:52.000 --> 18:55.134
and we couldn't tell how
advanced it was in the x-ray...

18:56.526 --> 18:58.485
But she's going to need
a new lung.

18:58.528 --> 19:01.401
[soft solemn music]

19:01.444 --> 19:03.142
- You can do that?

19:03.185 --> 19:04.752
You can give her a new lung?

19:04.795 --> 19:06.754
- Normally, yes.

19:06.797 --> 19:08.190
But because
you're undocumented--

19:08.234 --> 19:10.801
- Dr. Bloom says you treat
everyone here.

19:10.845 --> 19:12.499
- We do.
We do.

19:12.542 --> 19:15.066
But the Organ Transplant
Foundation, they won't put

19:15.110 --> 19:16.938
an undocumented person on their
recipient list,

19:16.981 --> 19:20.550
because post-operative care
requires....

19:20.594 --> 19:22.944
Well, stability.

19:22.987 --> 19:25.512
- And they don't think
we have that.

19:25.555 --> 19:26.904
- No.

19:26.948 --> 19:29.559
♪

19:29.603 --> 19:31.735
- What about me?

19:31.779 --> 19:32.997
Give her my lung.

19:33.041 --> 19:34.695
♪

19:34.738 --> 19:38.960
- Well, we can check to see
if you're a match,

19:39.003 --> 19:41.919
but they're won't be
any guarantee.

19:41.963 --> 19:43.921
- Any chance is better
than none.

19:43.965 --> 19:45.619
♪

19:45.662 --> 19:46.663
Please.

19:46.707 --> 19:50.145
♪

19:52.843 --> 19:54.758
- That leaves only
four recipients.

19:54.802 --> 19:56.934
- And we still have more
donors to talk to.

19:56.978 --> 19:58.588
- Let's hope they stay in.

19:58.632 --> 20:00.068
- Why do you think any of them

20:00.111 --> 20:01.678
will have a different reaction
than Tariq?

20:01.722 --> 20:03.158
They're good people,
but they're not giving

20:03.202 --> 20:04.812
out of the goodness
of their hearts.

20:04.855 --> 20:06.596
- Quid pro quo.

20:06.640 --> 20:08.555
- How's the, uh, chain going?

20:08.598 --> 20:10.078
- Don't ask.

20:10.121 --> 20:11.819
- So, uh, I have a patient
presenting with IPF.

20:11.862 --> 20:14.256
She needs a lung,
but she's undocumented.

20:14.300 --> 20:15.866
- No family matches?

20:15.910 --> 20:17.477
- She only has her father,
but he's not a match.

20:17.520 --> 20:19.087
I was hoping that maybe
you could call the Mayor,

20:19.130 --> 20:21.089
get her a visa, so we can get
her on the OTF list.

20:22.308 --> 20:24.484
[dramatic music]

20:24.527 --> 20:25.659
- Sharpe?

20:25.702 --> 20:29.532
♪

20:29.576 --> 20:30.838
- I don't see how this helps.

20:30.881 --> 20:32.056
- The HLA factors.

20:32.100 --> 20:34.537
Uh, let's get the whole team
in here.

20:34.581 --> 20:37.236
We might have a way
to save everyone.

20:39.803 --> 20:40.021
.

20:40.064 --> 20:42.980
- The chain fell apart when we
lost Tanya Mayer,

20:43.024 --> 20:44.982
but it looks like we have
a new match for Aminah.

20:45.026 --> 20:46.897
And that is Diego Morales.

20:46.941 --> 20:48.769
[dramatic music]

20:48.812 --> 20:49.857
- So the chain is complete?

20:49.900 --> 20:51.467
- It will be if Diego agrees

20:51.511 --> 20:52.903
to donate part of his liver.

20:52.947 --> 20:54.514
- Wait, how does Diego
donating his liver

20:54.557 --> 20:55.776
help his daughter?
She needs half a lung.

20:55.819 --> 20:57.038
- That's where the chain
comes in.

20:57.081 --> 20:58.735
We need the families
of the donors

20:58.779 --> 21:00.781
and the recipients to reach
out to their people

21:00.824 --> 21:02.652
to find anyone who might be
willing to donate

21:02.696 --> 21:05.525
their lung to Gianna.

21:05.568 --> 21:07.135
- Why would anyone do this

21:07.178 --> 21:09.006
when they weren't
willing to before?

21:09.050 --> 21:10.921
- Because they weren't getting
anything in return before.

21:10.965 --> 21:12.662
But now they would be saving
the lives

21:12.706 --> 21:14.708
of everyone in the chain,
including their loved one.

21:14.751 --> 21:15.970
It's a win-win.
Win, win--

21:16.013 --> 21:17.580
- We don't have a lot of time.

21:17.624 --> 21:19.190
Some of the recipients
won't make it past tomorrow.

21:19.234 --> 21:21.062
- Then we better do it quickly.

21:21.105 --> 21:23.630
♪

21:23.673 --> 21:25.109
- You becoming part
of this chain

21:25.153 --> 21:26.850
is our best bet
at saving Gianna.

21:26.894 --> 21:28.417
- We realize you may need
some time.

21:28.461 --> 21:29.766
- I'll do it.

21:31.812 --> 21:33.596
- You understand
what we're asking?

21:33.640 --> 21:35.206
- Give me the knife
and I'll do it myself.

21:35.250 --> 21:37.644
- Well, let's hold off on that,

21:37.687 --> 21:39.646
but we do appreciate
the enthusiasm.

21:39.689 --> 21:42.823
Um, now the hard part.

21:42.866 --> 21:45.565
- Are you seriously asking me
to donate a lung, too?

21:45.608 --> 21:47.393
- No, you would just be
the liver donor.

21:47.436 --> 21:48.959
What I'm asking for is help
finding someone

21:49.003 --> 21:50.613
willing to donate a portion
of their lung.

21:50.657 --> 21:52.093
A second donor.

21:52.136 --> 21:53.877
- So we start this
all over again.

21:53.921 --> 21:56.793
- This girl,
she is just a child?

21:56.837 --> 21:58.186
- 12 years old.

21:58.229 --> 22:00.710
The only person she has
is her father.

22:00.754 --> 22:01.929
- And he is not a match?

22:01.972 --> 22:03.844
[dramatic music]

22:03.887 --> 22:06.934
- Gianna can only qualify for
a "directed organ" transplant.

22:06.977 --> 22:08.457
Without it--
- No.

22:08.501 --> 22:11.155
We've done everything
you've told us to do.

22:11.199 --> 22:12.635
We've done enough.

22:12.679 --> 22:18.859
♪

22:18.902 --> 22:21.688
- Is there anyone else?

22:21.731 --> 22:23.472
Another family member?

22:23.516 --> 22:25.561
We need a lung donor
to make this work.

22:26.736 --> 22:28.608
- My sister was all
the family I had.

22:28.651 --> 22:30.523
And you know how that ended.

22:33.787 --> 22:36.006
- Peter Stein is getting antsy
about donating,

22:36.050 --> 22:37.878
and frankly, so are we.

22:37.921 --> 22:39.575
At some point we're gonna
have to pull the plug.

22:39.619 --> 22:41.229
- Just not yet.
Please.

22:41.272 --> 22:43.013
- I'll do what I can
on my end,

22:43.057 --> 22:44.798
but at this point,
I can't promise anything.

22:44.841 --> 22:46.495
- Okay, thanks.

22:46.539 --> 22:48.758
Dora, get me Iggy.
Oh.

22:48.802 --> 22:49.977
Hey.

22:51.195 --> 22:52.893
Hi.
- Hey.

22:52.936 --> 22:54.721
Guess what.

22:54.764 --> 22:57.550
Helen pulled some strings,
got us in with Dr. Britland.

22:57.593 --> 23:00.204
Best dental surgeon
in the city.

23:01.858 --> 23:03.991
But something came up.

23:04.034 --> 23:05.732
- I'm not trying to get out
of this, okay?

23:05.775 --> 23:08.517
I am just trying to rebuild
this transplant chain,

23:08.561 --> 23:10.519
Uh, one piece at a time.

23:10.563 --> 23:12.652
Until each piece falls
into place,

23:12.695 --> 23:16.220
but it just keeps
falling apart.

23:16.264 --> 23:17.831
♪

23:17.874 --> 23:19.267
- You know I'm on Team Max,
right?

23:19.310 --> 23:21.922
- [chuckles]
Of course I do.

23:21.965 --> 23:23.837
- No, I mean, I have banners
and hats and...

23:23.880 --> 23:26.840
- You have a hat?

23:26.883 --> 23:29.320
- But sometimes it feels like
I'm the only one.

23:29.364 --> 23:31.192
♪

23:31.235 --> 23:33.629
- You're not.
I promise.

23:33.673 --> 23:38.242
Look, I want this cancer out
of my body more than anything.

23:38.286 --> 23:40.070
♪

23:40.114 --> 23:42.943
I just have to push
this appointment a few hours.

23:42.986 --> 23:45.772
Just until I can
fix this chain.

23:45.815 --> 23:50.124
♪

23:50.167 --> 23:51.299
- Hey.

23:51.342 --> 23:53.910
Team Max.

23:53.954 --> 23:57.784
♪

23:57.827 --> 23:59.568
- Team Max.

23:59.612 --> 24:02.310
- I'm here to make it
100% clear to you what happens

24:02.353 --> 24:05.139
emotionally and physically
after organ donation.

24:05.182 --> 24:09.360
- Dr. Frome, Gianna and I
came here from Guatemala.

24:09.404 --> 24:11.232
I was police there.

24:11.275 --> 24:15.149
The gangs, they don't like it
if they cannot corrupt you.

24:16.411 --> 24:18.108
They threatened our lives.

24:18.152 --> 24:20.371
- That's why you left?
You fled.

24:23.026 --> 24:25.376
- When Gianna could not walk
and breathe at the same time,

24:25.420 --> 24:27.335
I carried her.

24:27.378 --> 24:30.381
And when we finally
go to New York...

24:32.645 --> 24:35.952
I made sure we were hidden,
so they could not send us back.

24:37.127 --> 24:38.738
And she got worse.

24:38.781 --> 24:41.088
This is my fault.

24:41.131 --> 24:42.872
And I'm going to fix it.

24:45.005 --> 24:47.660
It doesn't matter
what happens to me.

24:47.703 --> 24:50.053
[gentle melancholy music]

24:50.097 --> 24:52.229
- Okay.

24:52.273 --> 24:54.275
That's all I needed to hear.

24:54.318 --> 24:57.104
♪

24:57.147 --> 24:58.801
- Hey, I was just about
to head out.

24:58.845 --> 25:00.586
I wanted to see
if you needed anything.

25:00.629 --> 25:02.109
♪

25:02.152 --> 25:03.763
Oh.

25:03.806 --> 25:05.112
Are you okay?

25:05.155 --> 25:07.810
- [sobs]
I'm scared.

25:07.854 --> 25:09.203
♪

25:09.246 --> 25:13.294
I don't like being...alone.

25:13.337 --> 25:17.951
♪

25:17.994 --> 25:19.822
- You wanna know a secret?

25:22.259 --> 25:24.610
I don't like being alone
either.

25:24.653 --> 25:28.614
♪

25:28.657 --> 25:31.442
What do you say, you and I,

25:31.486 --> 25:34.271
we keep each other company
until your dad gets back?

25:34.315 --> 25:36.796
♪

25:36.839 --> 25:38.362
Yeah?
- Yeah.

25:38.406 --> 25:41.061
- Okay.
Come on, scoot over.

25:41.104 --> 25:44.151
♪

25:44.194 --> 25:46.022
Okay.

25:46.066 --> 25:47.328
Hey, you know,
Gemini's boyfriend

25:47.371 --> 25:49.722
was my very first crush.

25:49.765 --> 25:51.941
- But he's a one-eyed
meteor beast.

25:51.985 --> 25:54.074
- Yeah.

25:54.117 --> 25:56.206
Yeah, I was a weird kid.

25:56.250 --> 26:00.210
♪

26:00.254 --> 26:03.083
- We shared Gianna's case
with all the families

26:03.126 --> 26:04.867
in the Domino Transplant Chain.

26:04.911 --> 26:07.957
And it was a tough ask
of a perfect stranger

26:08.001 --> 26:10.699
to donate a part of their lung.

26:10.743 --> 26:13.746
- I, uh, I understand.

26:13.789 --> 26:15.704
- The thing is, Diego, um,

26:15.748 --> 26:18.925
we don't have a donor
for Gianna.

26:21.362 --> 26:22.450
We have 12.

26:22.493 --> 26:23.843
[uplifting music]

26:23.886 --> 26:25.366
Now with so many volunteers,

26:25.409 --> 26:29.675
we are almost sure to find
a match for Gianna today.

26:29.718 --> 26:36.769
♪

26:39.293 --> 26:40.990
[pager buzzes and dings]

26:41.948 --> 26:43.514
What is it?

26:43.558 --> 26:45.908
- She just stopped breathing.
- BP's dropping.

26:45.952 --> 26:47.388
- Got any room on her
dopamine drip?

26:47.431 --> 26:48.824
- Maxed out.
So is the dobutamine.

26:48.868 --> 26:50.173
- Start levophed.
- Start levophed.

26:50.217 --> 26:51.827
- We've got this.
- Heart rate's up to 120.

26:51.871 --> 26:53.220
Are you sure her heart
can tolerate the levo?

26:53.263 --> 26:54.961
- No, but do it anyway.
- Reynolds?

26:55.004 --> 26:56.353
- We've got this.

26:59.530 --> 27:02.490
[intense music]

27:02.533 --> 27:03.839
♪

27:03.883 --> 27:05.885
Come on, Gianna.

27:05.928 --> 27:07.408
Come on.

27:07.451 --> 27:09.062
Come on, come on.

27:09.105 --> 27:12.935
♪

27:15.764 --> 27:15.982
.

27:16.025 --> 27:17.984
- Gianna's heart is failing,
Diego.

27:18.027 --> 27:19.638
Her lungs are so scarred

27:19.681 --> 27:21.683
that her heart can't pump
blood through them.

27:21.727 --> 27:24.686
[solemn music]

27:24.730 --> 27:26.166
- We have to take her
to the OR

27:26.209 --> 27:28.081
to put her on an aortic
balloon pump.

27:28.124 --> 27:30.213
That will stabilize
her condition and hopefully

27:30.257 --> 27:31.693
it will help her heart recover.

27:31.737 --> 27:34.130
- But until it does,

27:34.174 --> 27:36.176
she's not strong enough

27:36.219 --> 27:37.699
to withstand transplant
surgery.

27:37.743 --> 27:39.788
I'm sorry.

27:39.832 --> 27:45.315
♪

27:45.359 --> 27:47.013
- Take care of my little girl.

27:47.056 --> 27:48.667
♪

27:48.710 --> 27:49.842
- We'll give you some time
with her.

27:49.885 --> 27:56.936
♪

28:01.767 --> 28:04.595
- I really thought we were
gonna make this chain work.

28:04.639 --> 28:05.858
- You're giving up?

28:05.901 --> 28:07.120
- There's nothing else
to do today,

28:07.163 --> 28:09.949
except hope everyone hangs on.

28:09.992 --> 28:13.039
[indistinct PA announcement]

28:19.088 --> 28:20.350
- Is Gianna okay?

28:20.394 --> 28:22.091
- We're getting her
to the OR now.

28:22.135 --> 28:24.137
Uh, can we talk?

28:24.180 --> 28:26.313
- I don't know, can we?

28:26.356 --> 28:28.184
It seems like you've been
doing everything you can

28:28.228 --> 28:29.925
not to talk to me.

28:30.796 --> 28:32.058
- I deserve that.

28:32.101 --> 28:33.059
- I got more,
you wanna hear 'em?

28:33.102 --> 28:35.017
- Okay, look, uh, Evie and I

28:35.061 --> 28:37.106
have been spending
a lot of time together.

28:37.150 --> 28:40.066
And our history makes that,
you know, complicated.

28:40.109 --> 28:41.894
And awkward.

28:41.937 --> 28:43.286
- Not for me.

28:43.330 --> 28:44.766
- Really?

28:44.810 --> 28:46.289
- I introduced the two of you.

28:46.333 --> 28:48.770
I mean, shouldn't that prove
that I'm fine with this?

28:48.814 --> 28:50.293
Or do you think I just like
torturing myself?

28:50.337 --> 28:51.817
- I mean...

28:51.860 --> 28:54.645
- Shut up.
Come on, stop being weird.

28:54.689 --> 28:56.735
We're friends and we're fine.

28:56.778 --> 28:59.650
Now can you just please go
and fix Gianna?

29:01.261 --> 29:02.784
- All right.

29:17.843 --> 29:20.106
- You can't lock me in here!

29:20.149 --> 29:22.151
- Okay, we can talk about that

29:22.195 --> 29:23.674
but not while you're yelling.

29:24.850 --> 29:26.329
- [screams]

29:28.027 --> 29:30.290
It's not even my fault!

29:30.333 --> 29:32.292
Janine was messing
with my machine.

29:32.335 --> 29:36.731
And I told her to stop it
and she wouldn't!

29:36.775 --> 29:38.820
- Wow, you really cared
about that project, huh?

29:38.864 --> 29:39.908
- Yeah.
- Okay.

29:39.952 --> 29:42.693
So then, why did you break it?

29:50.397 --> 29:52.965
All right, um...

29:53.008 --> 29:56.795
Do me a favor and just
close your eyes for a second.

29:58.448 --> 30:00.015
Jemma, close them.

30:02.278 --> 30:04.672
Close them, please.
Thank you.

30:04.715 --> 30:07.240
All right, now I want you
to picture that machine.

30:07.283 --> 30:09.851
I want you to see it broken
in pieces all over the ground.

30:10.809 --> 30:12.462
How does that make you feel?

30:12.506 --> 30:14.856
- Sad, I guess.
- Okay.

30:14.900 --> 30:15.988
Why sad?

30:16.031 --> 30:17.250
- Because it's a waste.

30:17.293 --> 30:19.295
- All right, what else?

30:23.386 --> 30:25.867
- It's...

30:25.911 --> 30:27.913
sad because...

30:31.003 --> 30:33.919
It's useless now
and nobody wants it.

30:35.311 --> 30:36.791
- Jemma.

30:36.835 --> 30:38.488
- I know what you're gonna say.

30:38.532 --> 30:40.708
- You do?

30:40.751 --> 30:42.971
Okay, all right, smarty-pants.
Then tell me.

30:43.015 --> 30:44.799
What am I gonna say?

30:55.157 --> 30:57.029
- No one wants me.

30:59.901 --> 31:01.468
- Why would I say that?

31:03.209 --> 31:04.906
It's not true.
- Yes, it is.

31:04.950 --> 31:07.387
- No, it's not.
Blanca wants you.

31:07.430 --> 31:09.084
- Yeah, today she does.

31:11.782 --> 31:13.349
Someday she won't.

31:18.964 --> 31:21.227
Look, I'm gonna mess it up.
I always do.

31:21.270 --> 31:23.490
- No, I don't believe that.
Not for a second.

31:24.534 --> 31:28.321
I know that trusting people
is scary.

31:28.364 --> 31:31.280
Th--that's the scariest thing.

31:31.324 --> 31:33.935
But when it comes to family,

31:33.979 --> 31:37.112
that's just the price
of admission.

31:37.156 --> 31:38.940
That's the way it goes.

31:40.899 --> 31:43.902
And nobody deserves a family
more than you do.

31:44.598 --> 31:46.165
Nobody.

31:48.297 --> 31:49.820
Trust me.

31:53.346 --> 31:55.174
You don't have to go.

31:56.566 --> 31:58.960
But...

31:59.004 --> 32:02.268
If you do decide to take
that leap of faith,

32:02.311 --> 32:04.531
I'll be there with you.

32:04.574 --> 32:06.228
♪

32:06.272 --> 32:09.492
[siren wailing]

32:09.536 --> 32:12.191
- I hate feeling like
I'm giving up on these people.

32:12.234 --> 32:14.280
- Max, when have you ever
given up on anyone?

32:14.323 --> 32:15.977
Right now, if you don't
take care of yourself,

32:16.021 --> 32:17.196
how are you gonna take care
of them?

32:17.239 --> 32:19.154
- Max.
- What's going on?

32:19.198 --> 32:20.503
Is everyone okay?
- Everyone's fine.

32:20.547 --> 32:22.114
Diego?

32:22.157 --> 32:23.463
- May I still give
to the chain?

32:23.506 --> 32:25.987
[soft uplifting music]

32:26.031 --> 32:29.034
[speaking in Spanish]

32:43.309 --> 32:44.484
- What did he say?

32:44.527 --> 32:47.139
♪

32:47.182 --> 32:49.010
- The Domino Chain's a go.

32:52.448 --> 32:52.666
.

32:52.709 --> 32:53.972
- Okay.

32:54.015 --> 32:55.538
I hereby bequeath unto you

32:55.582 --> 32:57.671
the "Holy Sticky Notes."

32:57.714 --> 32:58.977
- Such an honor.

32:59.020 --> 33:00.891
- We're gonna be late.
- Text me, okay?

33:00.935 --> 33:02.415
I wanna know everything
that's going on,

33:02.458 --> 33:03.677
every step of the way.

33:03.720 --> 33:05.026
- Absolutely.

33:05.070 --> 33:06.593
That sounds like a great use
of my time.

33:06.636 --> 33:07.986
- I want a full play-by-play,
right?

33:08.029 --> 33:09.988
Leave no patient's condition
un-texted.

33:10.031 --> 33:12.033
Leave no surgeon's incision
un-communicated.

33:12.077 --> 33:14.383
- Max, you're headed into
quadruple molar extraction.

33:14.427 --> 33:15.645
You'll be under anesthesia
for hours.

33:15.689 --> 33:16.995
- I can multitask.

33:17.038 --> 33:18.431
- Just please say "okay",
so I can push

33:18.474 --> 33:19.998
him into a passing cab.
- Okay.

33:20.041 --> 33:21.521
I'll text so frequently,
you'll need a new data plan.

33:21.564 --> 33:23.088
- That's what I'm talking
about.

33:29.137 --> 33:32.097
[Ben Howard's "Promise"]

33:32.140 --> 33:39.191
♪

33:54.554 --> 34:00.603
- ♪ And meet

34:00.647 --> 34:02.910
♪ Me there

34:02.953 --> 34:04.738
♪ Bundles of flowers

34:04.781 --> 34:07.088
♪ We'll wade through
the hours of cold ♪

34:07.132 --> 34:10.961
♪

34:11.005 --> 34:12.441
♪ Winter

34:12.485 --> 34:13.790
- Good news?

34:13.834 --> 34:15.488
- Your organ just landed.

34:15.531 --> 34:16.967
♪

34:17.011 --> 34:20.188
I'll be here with you
every step of the way.

34:20.232 --> 34:21.929
♪

34:21.972 --> 34:26.977
- ♪ Shelter

34:27.021 --> 34:29.632
♪ As we go

34:29.676 --> 34:32.635
♪

34:32.679 --> 34:35.638
[machine beeping]

34:35.682 --> 34:42.732
♪

34:50.218 --> 34:52.046
- Go ahead.

34:52.090 --> 34:58.705
- ♪ And promise

34:58.748 --> 35:01.621
♪ Me this

35:01.664 --> 35:03.666
♪ You'll wait for me only

35:03.710 --> 35:06.669
♪ Scared of the lonely arms

35:06.713 --> 35:11.065
♪

35:11.109 --> 35:16.026
♪ Surface

35:16.070 --> 35:18.899
♪ Far below these birds

35:18.942 --> 35:21.162
- Welcome home, kiddo.

35:21.206 --> 35:28.213
♪

35:48.015 --> 35:52.672
- ♪ And maybe

35:52.715 --> 35:55.153
♪ Just maybe

35:55.196 --> 35:57.546
♪ I'll come home

35:57.590 --> 36:04.640
♪

36:05.641 --> 36:07.295
- Matty's in recovery.

36:07.339 --> 36:12.735
♪

36:12.779 --> 36:15.564
Congratulations.

36:15.608 --> 36:17.914
Your chain is complete.

36:17.958 --> 36:19.307
- Our chain.

36:19.351 --> 36:22.876
Do you know, in Oncology,

36:22.919 --> 36:24.617
you get so few wins.

36:24.660 --> 36:27.750
It becomes harder and harder
to believe

36:27.794 --> 36:29.317
that things will ever work out.

36:29.361 --> 36:31.798
- Oh, I thought for sure
this would not work out.

36:31.841 --> 36:33.016
♪

36:33.060 --> 36:34.801
- But it did.

36:34.844 --> 36:37.238
- ♪ Who am I
darling to you ♪

36:37.282 --> 36:38.805
♪ Who am I

36:38.848 --> 36:40.763
♪ Gonna tell you stories

36:40.807 --> 36:42.243
♪ Of mine

36:42.287 --> 36:44.027
♪

36:44.071 --> 36:45.942
- Welcome back.

36:45.986 --> 36:52.993
♪

36:54.299 --> 36:56.257
- Gianna.

36:56.301 --> 36:58.128
How is she?

36:58.172 --> 36:59.826
♪

36:59.869 --> 37:01.784
- Ask her yourself.

37:01.828 --> 37:06.876
♪

37:06.920 --> 37:09.879
- Como estas, Papi?

37:09.923 --> 37:12.186
- We were able to shore up
her heart enough

37:12.230 --> 37:13.622
to do her transplant.

37:13.666 --> 37:16.059
♪

37:16.103 --> 37:17.670
- She got her lung?

37:17.713 --> 37:21.630
- ♪ Just maybe
I'll come home ♪

37:21.674 --> 37:23.241
- Your daughter is a fighter.

37:23.284 --> 37:25.025
Just like Gemini.

37:25.068 --> 37:28.202
♪

37:28.246 --> 37:32.075
- She gets it from her mother.

37:32.119 --> 37:35.165
- I get it from you, Papi.

37:35.209 --> 37:39.126
♪

37:39.169 --> 37:40.997
- Thank you.

37:41.041 --> 37:43.261
Thank you, doctor.

37:43.304 --> 37:45.263
- Oh.

37:45.306 --> 37:47.090
♪

37:47.134 --> 37:49.049
I only saved one life today.

37:49.092 --> 37:50.964
♪

37:51.007 --> 37:52.966
You saved six.

37:53.009 --> 37:58.188
♪

37:58.232 --> 38:02.062
- ♪ Who am I
darling to you ♪

38:02.105 --> 38:04.369
- And that was awesome.

38:04.412 --> 38:06.153
- Yes, it was.

38:06.196 --> 38:08.329
- Hey, you wanna have lunch
with me and Evie?

38:08.373 --> 38:10.331
Her favorite spot's this place
on 23rd that literally

38:10.375 --> 38:12.333
puts everything on a donut.

38:12.377 --> 38:14.857
- [chuckles]
- ♪ Darling for you

38:14.901 --> 38:16.424
♪ Who am I

38:16.468 --> 38:17.860
♪ Could be a burden

38:17.904 --> 38:21.037
- As tempting as that sounds,

38:21.081 --> 38:23.431
I think I'm just gonna
head home and chill.

38:23.475 --> 38:26.739
- Chill?

38:26.782 --> 38:27.783
- Later.

38:27.827 --> 38:29.132
- ♪ Who am I

38:29.176 --> 38:30.830
♪ Could be a burden

38:30.873 --> 38:31.918
♪ Who am I

38:31.961 --> 38:33.833
- Don't keep her waiting.

38:33.876 --> 38:35.487
- ♪ Who am I

38:35.530 --> 38:38.316
♪ I come alone here

38:38.359 --> 38:41.971
♪

38:42.015 --> 38:43.364
♪ I come alone

38:43.408 --> 38:45.366
- Hey, what are you doing here?

38:45.410 --> 38:47.977
- So the thing is...

38:48.021 --> 38:49.805
I do wanna walk
into work with you.

38:49.849 --> 38:56.899
♪

39:00.207 --> 39:02.252
- Haven't seen you
in a while, Dr. Bloom.

39:02.296 --> 39:03.515
Welcome home.

39:03.558 --> 39:10.783
♪

39:19.313 --> 39:21.446
- Bronx General
Emergency Department.

39:21.489 --> 39:23.099
- It's Dr. Lauren Bloom.

39:23.143 --> 39:24.884
Can I still pick up
that shift tonight?

39:24.927 --> 39:26.320
- We could always use
another set of hands.

39:26.364 --> 39:27.887
I'll put you down.

39:27.930 --> 39:34.981
♪

39:53.913 --> 39:56.002
[muffled barking]

39:56.045 --> 39:59.092
[muffled honking]

40:14.194 --> 40:15.848
- Morning, sleepyhead.

40:17.632 --> 40:19.591
Ready for breakfast?

40:19.634 --> 40:22.115
Well, lunch.

40:22.158 --> 40:24.247
Bone broth.

40:24.291 --> 40:25.510
Yummy.

40:34.040 --> 40:36.825
Oh, Helen texted you all right.

40:36.869 --> 40:39.001
So many texts.

40:39.045 --> 40:42.309
Lot of, uh,
complicated doctor talk.

40:42.352 --> 40:44.267
But there's only one thing
you need to know right now.

40:44.311 --> 40:48.358
"Our Domino Chain
was a complete success.

40:48.402 --> 40:50.883
Thank you for never
letting us lose hope."

40:53.625 --> 40:55.365
- [moans]

40:59.152 --> 41:01.502
- You can read the rest after
you've had your bone broth.

41:16.474 --> 41:19.433
[Yo La Tengo's
"Our Way to Fall"]

41:19.477 --> 41:26.484
♪

41:36.581 --> 41:39.975
- ♪ You'll try and try

41:40.019 --> 41:42.456
♪ Even if it lasts an hour

41:42.500 --> 41:45.981
♪ With all our might

41:46.025 --> 41:48.680
♪ Try and make it ours

41:48.723 --> 41:51.073
♪ 'Cause we're on our way

41:51.117 --> 41:55.164
♪ We're on our way
to fall in love ♪

41:55.208 --> 41:58.254
♪

41:58.298 --> 42:00.648
♪ Yeah, we're on our way
to fall in love ♪

42:00.692 --> 42:04.217
- We'll do it together.

42:04.260 --> 42:06.306
One piece at a time.

42:06.349 --> 42:10.440
Until each piece
falls into place.

42:10.484 --> 42:14.140
- ♪ We're on our way
to fall in love ♪

42:14.183 --> 42:15.707
- I got you.

42:15.750 --> 42:19.972
♪
